@NODE requirements "hotlist.module: requirements"

@{fg shine}Requirements@{fg text}
@{fg shine}----------------------@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}--@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--- -- -  -@{fg text}
This module requires Directory Opus version 5.5 -- it will not work with
version 5.11 or other earlier versions.

From v1.2 onwards, hotlist.module also requires AmigaOS 2.1 or above. If
you are still using OS2.0, 2.1 is only a software upgrade and there really
is no excuse. You should be using 3.x anyway!

If you're using a @{b}pirate@{ub} copy of Opus5.5, I'll pretend it's @{b}YOU@{ub} I'm
shooting at in Quake and Descent 2. @{fg shine}=8-|@{fg text}  ...and something nasty might
just happen to either your harddisk or your genitals, depending on my
mood and the phase of the moon.

Apart from that there are no unusual requirements. If you have any
problems running it on your system, please @{" contact me " LINK credits} and I will do
my best to help out, or write to the Directory Opus 5 mailing list.

@endnode
@NODE introduction "hotlist.module: introduction"

@{fg shine}Introduction: What is a hotlist?
@{fg shine}----------------------@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}--@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--- -- -  -@{fg text}
Anyone who has used a web browser such as Netscape, IBrowse, Voyager,
Lynx, or, God forbid, Microsoft Internet Explorer (don't believe the hype,
it is complete crap, IMO) will be familiar with the concept of a hotlist.
Anyone who hasn't used a web browser is a nobody and can stop reading
right now... Nah, @{i}just kidding. @{ui}

In a web browser you can keep a list of all your favourate web sites which
you can call up at any moment to select a site and jump right to it
without having to search around the entire web for the link. Obviously
you cannot jump straight to the page if your net connection is buggered
up like mine usually is, but that's another story and it's not important
right now.

This hotlist.module offers a similar feature for Directory Opus 5.5,
except that instead of web sites you put your most used directories in
the hotlist for quick access. I don't know about you, but I have so many
assigns in my system that finding the right one in the built-in Opus
devicelist takes up to a few seconds, and I can't afford to waste that
much time when there are important things to do like look at my latest
Aminet downloads. You're not limited to assigns and directories, of
course, you can put devices and even files into the hotlist.

If you're still confused, read the rest of the guide and then play
around with it, it's not very difficult to use once you know what
you're doing.

@endnode
@NODE installation "hotlist.module: installation"

@{fg shine}Installation:@{fg text}
@{fg shine}----------------------@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}--@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--- -- -  -@{fg text}
@{b}Use the supplied Installer script, it won't bite.@{ub}

@{fg fill}o@{fg text} The Installer script will inform you about everything it does and you
  are able to confirm, skip, or abort before most actions.
@{fg fill}o@{fg text} The Installer script will put everything where it is supposed to go.
@{fg fill}o@{fg text} The Installer script will not overwrite newer versions of the module
  or the AmigaGuide, and if you already have an icon for the guide it
  will leave it alone, saving your snapshot/image/tooltype information.
@{fg fill}o@{fg text} The Installer script will not copy over your hotlist filetype if one
  already exists in @{fg fill}DOpus5:filetypes/@{fg text} or @{fg fill}DOpus5:Storage/filetypes/@{fg text},
  saving any changes you have made to it.

If you are a completely paranoid psycho and really must install it by hand,
do the following:

First, CHILL OUT! Now think about using the Installer script, I didn't
write it for the fun of it, you know.

If you are using my old @{fg fill}hotlist.dopus5@{fg text} ARexx module you should move it
from @{fg fill}DOpus5:modules@{fg text} to @{fg fill}DOpus5:storage/modules@{fg text}.
-- @{b}YOU CANNOT HAVE BOTH INSTALLED AS THEY WILL CLASH.@{ub}
You might as well delete your old @{fg fill}dopus5:system/hotlist.config@{fg text} file as it is
not used by this new module. (Sorry, you'll have to remake your hotlist.)

Now just copy the file @{fg fill}hotlist.module@{fg text} to @{fg fill}DOpus5:modules@{fg text}. You may have
to reboot or restart Opus, especially if you were using the old ARexx
hotlist, but if you're lucky you won't.

You should also copy this @{fg fill}guide@{fg text} and its icon to @{fg fill}DOpus5:Help@{fg text}.

If you want to install a filetype which will let you double-click on a
hotlist.module config file in a normal lister to read the hotlist into the
lister copy the file @{fg fill}filetypes/hotlist.module Hotlist@{fg text} to @{fg fill}DOpus5:filetypes/@{fg text}.
If you don't want the filetype it's probably a good idea to copy it to
@{fg fill}DOpus5:Storage/filetypes/@{fg text} anyway, in case you want it in the future. If
you want to create the filetype by hand, see the @{" description " LINK filetype}.

The filetype will also add an @{fg fill}Open Hotlist@{fg text} entry to the icon-mode
pop-up-menu for hotlist config files.

If you don't want to use the built-in English strings and a catalog exists
for your preferred language, copy the appropriate directory from @{fg fill}catalogs/@{fg text}
to @{fg fill}DOpus5:catalogs/@{fg text}.

@endnode
@NODE filetype "hotlist.module: the filetype"

@{fg shine}The Filetype@{fg text}
@{fg shine}----------------------@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}--@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--- -- -  -@{fg text}
The following description is for a filetype which will will let you
double-click on a hotlist.module config file in a normal lister to read
the hotlist into the lister.

Also, in icon-mode the right-mouse-button pop-up-menu for hotlist config
files will have an @{fg fill}Open Hotlist@{fg text} item which you can use to open a new
hotlist window for the file.

This filetype will have been installed for you by the Installer script
unless you either didn't use the script or opted not to install it.

@{fg shine}Class Information@{fg text}

	@{fg fill}Suggested name:@{fg text}	hotlist.module Hotlist
	@{fg fill}Suggested ID:@{fg text}	HOTLIST
	@{fg fill}Priority:@{fg text}	1	@{i}Must be above IFF type's priority. @{ui}

	@{fg fill}Match Instruction:@{fg text}
	@{b}Match FORM@{ub}	DOHL

@{fg shine}Double-Click Event@{fg text}

	@{b}AmigaDOS@{ub}   rx 'address {Qp} command hotlist CONFIG {f} LISTER {Ql}'
	@{fg fill}<all flags off>@{fg text}

@{fg shine}Icon Menu:@{fg text} Open Hotlist

	@{b}AmigaDOS@{ub}   rx 'address {Qp} command hotlist CONFIG {f} NEW'
	@{fg fill}<all flags off>@{fg text}

@ENDNODE
@NODE settingup "hotlist.module: setting up"

@{fg shine}Setting Up@{fg text}
@{fg shine}----------------------@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}--@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--- -- -  -@{fg text}
Once installed, this module adds a command called @{fg fill}Hotlist@{fg text} to Opus.

The @{fg fill}Hotlist@{fg text} command will now be shown in the pop-up list of commands with
all the other internal commands of Opus.

If you were using my old ARexx hotlist module and installed by hand
without moving it to storage first (can't you people READ?) you only
have yourself to blame if something goes wrong. :-)

You can setup a function which runs the @{fg fill}Hotlist@{fg text} command wherever you
want in Opus. Here are my suggestions:

@{b}1) @{ub}On the @{fg fill}scripts/doubleclick@{fg text} event so that when you doubleclick on the
   main Opus window you get a new lister with a Hotlist in it.

@{b}2) @{ub}On a button bank so that you can just click the button at any time to
   open a new lister with a Hotlist in it.

@{b}3) @{ub}On the lister toolbar so that when you're using a lister you can change
   it into a Hotlist at the click of a button.

An example button bank should have come with hotlist.module which contains
example buttons which open hotlists. If you opted to install it when you
used the Installer script you can open the button bank by double-clicking
the file @{fg fill}Hotlist-examples@{fg text} in @{fg fill}DOpus5:buttons/@{fg text}. Otherwise, you should find the
file in the hotlist.module distribution archive.

It is also possible to setup a filetype which will let you double-click on
a hotlist.module config file in a normal lister to read the hotlist into
the lister. Unless you chose not to, such a filetype should have been
installed by the Installer script. Instructions on creating the filetype
by hand can be found in the @{" installation section " LINK installation}.

The filetype will also add an @{fg fill}Open Hotlist@{fg text} entry to the icon-mode
pop-up-menu for hotlist config files.

@endnode
@NODE arguments "hotlist.module: arguments"

@{fg shine}Arguments@{fg text}
@{fg shine}----------------------@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}--@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--- -- -  -@{fg text}
@{b}YOU DISGUSTING, FILTHY PIECE OF SLIME...@{ub}
@{i}Oh, sorry, Arguments is down the hall. @{ui}

Normally, when the @{fg fill}Hotlist@{fg text} command is executed the hotlist will take over
the current source lister, or create a new lister if there isn't an
available source lister.

Note that if you execute the command from a lister toolbar it will always
take over the lister whose toolbar you used, regardless of whether it was
a source lister or not.

Unless told otherwise, all hotlists will use the file
@{fg fill}DOpus5:System/Hotlist.prefs@{fg text} to store settings.

You can use the following arguments to modify this behaviour:

@{fg shine}NEW@{fg text} (@{b}optional switch@{ub})
@{fg fill}---------------------@{fg text}
If you specify the NEW switch (like "@{b}Hotlist NEW@{ub}") the function will
always open a new lister for the hotlist, even if there is a source lister.
Among other things, this is something good to include if you are using the
command on the @{fg fill}scripts/doubleclick@{fg text} event as it provides you with a fast way
to get a new lister open @{b}and@{ub} the new lister starts off with a hotlist so
you can get to where you want to super-quick. Turbo, even.

@{fg shine}CONFIG@{fg text} (@{b}optional keyword@{ub})
@{fg fill}-------------------------@{fg text}
You can have as many different hotlist configs as you like, just specify
the path of the file you want to use with this argument.

For example, "@{b}Hotlist NEW T:Temphotlist.prefs@{ub}", or,
             "@{b}Hotlist S:Hotlist.prefs@{ub}".

If you wanted you could have a bank of buttons which pop-up different
hotlists.

The settings are stored in an IFF prefs file, the format of which is not
compatible with that used by my old @{fg fill}hotlist.dopus5@{fg text} ARexx script, or that
used by Greg Perry's (unreleased) hotlist program from about a year ago.

@{fg shine}LISTER@{fg text} (@{b}optional keyword@{ub})
@{fg fill}-------------------------@{fg text}
If you want the hotlist to appear in a certain lister, specify its handle
using the LISTER keyword. Do not use this argument unless you know what
you are doing.

For example, "@{b}Hotlist LISTER 137123636@{ub}".

@endnode
@NODE using "hotlist.module: using hotlists"

@{fg shine}Using Hotlists@{fg text}
@{fg shine}----------------------@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}--@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--- -- -  -@{fg text}
See the section on @{" setting up " LINK settingup} for information on how to open new
Hotlists, and so on.

@{" Adding Entries " LINK u_adding_entries}
@{" Changing Entries " LINK u_changing_entries}
@{" Removing Entries " LINK u_removing_entries}
@{" Using Entries " LINK u_using_entries}
@{" The Path Gadget " LINK u_path_gadget} & re-reading the config.
@{" The Parent Gadget " LINK u_parent_gadget}
@{" Snapshots " LINK u_snapshots}

@endnode
@NODE u_adding_entries "hotlist.module: adding entries"

@{fg shine}Adding Entries:@{fg text}
@{fg shine}----------------------@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}--@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--- -- -  -@{fg text}
Drag'n'drop a device, drawer, or file from another Opus lister or from
the main Opus window, or just about anywhere else to add it to the Hotlist.
You will be asked for a name to give the entry. You can drop more than one
thing at once.

You can make a new entry from scratch by pressing your normal @{fg fill}Makedir@{fg text}
button from the lister toolbar. You'll be asked for a path (you can pop-up
a file-requester or just type it in) and then a name.

The hotlist module will automatically detect whether the entry is a
device, a file, or a directory and will colour it differently depending
on the type.

If the file you drop is recognised as a hotlist.module config file it will
be given a special colour. Also, if you ever specify a file which cannot
be found (strictly, which cannot be Lock()'ed) the entry will be created
as if it pointed to a hotlist.module config file so that you can
@{" double click " LINK u_using_entries} it to create a new config file with that name.

You can copy entries from other hotlists (whether or not they use the same
config file) using drag'n'drop. You'll only be asked to name the entry if
there is already an entry with the same name.

You can duplicate existing entries by selecting those which you want to
duplciate and clicking your standard @{fg fill}Duplicate@{fg text} toolbar button. You will
be able to change the path (optional) and the name (mandatory) of the new
entry. This is most useful when you want several similar entries.

@endnode
@NODE u_changing_entries "hotlist.module: changing entries"

@{fg shine}Changing Entries:@{fg text}
@{fg shine}----------------------@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}--@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--- -- -  -@{fg text}
Hilight the entries you want to change and then press your normal @{fg fill}Rename@{fg text}
lister toolbar button. You'll be able to change the path and name of
the entries you selected.

The type of an entry is only checked when it is added. If you wish to
update an entry's type, for example if a directory is now a file, use
your @{fg fill}Rename@{fg text} button but leave the path and name the same as they were.

@endnode
@NODE u_removing_entries "hotlist.module: removing entries"

@{fg shine}Removing Entries:@{fg text}
@{fg shine}----------------------@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}--@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--- -- -  -@{fg text}
Hilight the entries you want to delete and then press your normal @{fg fill}Delete@{fg text}
lister toolbar button. Once you confirm the delete the entries will be
removed.

@{i}The only thing which is deleted is the entry in the hotlist -- the actual
device/directory/file is left untouched. @{uI}

@endnode
@NODE u_using_entries "hotlist.module: using entries"

@{fg shine}Using Entries:@{fg text}
@{fg shine}----------------------@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}--@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--- -- -  -@{fg text}
If you double click a directory or device it will be read into the lister.
If you hold @{fg fill}shift@{fg text} down it will be read into a new lister, leaving the hotlist
open. (If you have a 3-button mouse and run a MMBShift util you can hold
MMB instead of shift, which is nice.)

If you drag'n'drop a directory or device to another Opus lister it will
read the path into the lister and leave the hotlist open.

If you doubleclick a file it will have it's @{fg fill}doubleclick@{fg text} action run on it
as if you doubleclicked on the real file.

If you doubleclick a hotlist.module config file the existing hotlist will
be replaced by that contained in the file. You can press the @{" parent " LINK u_parent_gadget}
gadget to return to the previous hotlist. If you hold @{fg fill}shift@{fg text} when you
doubleclick a hotlist.module config file a new hotlist will open using it.

If you drag'n'drop a hotlist.module config file from a hotlist to another
Opus lister it will read the hotlist from the file into the lister.

@endnode
@NODE u_path_gadget "hotlist.module: the path gadget & re-reading the config"

@{fg shine}The path gadget & re-reading the config:@{fg text}
@{fg shine}----------------------@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}--@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--- -- -  -@{fg text}
The path gadget works like in other listers -- type in a path and it'll
be read into the lister. Activate the path gadget and then just
hit return and it'll 'rescan' (i.e. it re-reads the config file).

You can also cause the config file to be re-read by using a button with
@{fg fill}Scandir@{fg text} on it, just like you can normal listers.

Also, running @{fg fill}Hotlist@{fg text} on a hotlist lister causes a config re-read.

@endnode
@NODE u_parent_gadget "hotlist.module: the parent gadget"

@{fg shine}The Parent Gadget:@{fg text}
@{fg shine}----------------------@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}--@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--- -- -  -@{fg text}
If the hotlist takes over an old source lister, pressing the Parent gadget
returns you to the path displayed before the hotlist appeared. If you hold
@{fg fill}shift@{fg text} when you click the parent gadget the old path is read into a new
lister and the hotlist remains open. (If you have a 3-button mouse and run
a MMBShift util you can hold MMB instead of shift, which is nice.)

If the hotlist created a new lister, pressing the Parent gadget will cause
DisplayBeep() to be called which will, depending on your AmigaOS Sound
Preferences, flash the screen, make a beep noise, play a sample, or a
combination. This is extremely useful should you wish to simulate a
disco in the comfort of your own home with your trusty Amiga.

If you reached the current hotlist via another hotlist by doubleclicking
an entry for its config file, you can use the parent gadget to backtrack
to previous config files. If you hold @{fg fill}shift@{fg text} a new hotlist will open for
the old config file, leaving the current hotlist as it is.

@endnode
@NODE u_snapshots "hotlist.module: snapshots"

@{fg shine}Snapshots:@{fg text}
@{fg shine}----------------------@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}--@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--- -- -  -@{fg text}
You can Snapshot and Unsnapshot hotlist listers in the same way you can
normal listers using the @{fg fill}Snapshot@{fg text} and @{fg fill}Unsnapshot@{fg text} items in the lister
menu and the @{fg fill}Snapshot@{fg text} item in the lister pop-up.

Obviously, the snapshot position is only used when a new lister is openned
for the hotlist. When unsnapshot the lister opens under the mouse pointer.

@endnode
@NODE multihotlists "hotlist.module: using multiple hotlists"

@{fg shine}Using Multiple Hotlists:@{fg text}
@{fg shine}----------------------@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}--@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--- -- -  -@{fg text}
It should be perfectly safe to use as many hotlists as you want at the same
time. Any changes you make in one hotlist will be reflected in all other
hotlists using the same config file, and a semaphore is used to make sure
that only one hotlist may change config data at any given time.

When you see a message saying @{fg fill}@{i}Config in use, waiting... @{ui}@{fg text}it means another
hotlist is writting to its config file. This should not take long, and
normal operation should resume after a short delay.

Please note that if you store the config file on a device whose filesystem
does not support notification it will still not be possible for two
hotlists to write to the config file at the same time, but it will be
possible for you to lose entries. For example, if two hotlists are using
the same config file and you add three items to one and then a different
item to the other, the first three items will be lost from the config file.
Apart from this kind of thing, though, you can have as many hotlists open
as you like. @{b}Usually you won't have to worry about this at all, as most
modern filesystems support notification.@{ub}

@endnode
@NODE history "hotlist.module: history"

@{fg shine}History:
@{fg shine}----------------------@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}--@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--- -- -  -@{fg text}
@{fg shine}v1.0 -- 27/Sep/1996@{fg text}
@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{i}Initial release. @{ui}

@{fg shine}v1.1 -- 03/Oct/1996@{fg text}
@{fg fill}o@{fg text} In v1.0 certain events (e.g. dropping an icon from the main Opus window)
  would wrongly bring up an error message telling you not to drop entries
  between a hotlist and other handlers.
@{fg fill}o@{fg text} No longer sits waiting forever when called from a devicelist.
  (It now opens a new lister which is better than before. Unfortunately
  it isn't possible, AFAIK, to take over the devicelist itself.)
@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Tidied source up quite a bit & improved the makefile a little (I think).
@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Fixed bug where "/" not appended to the path returned when the
  file-requester was used to add a new entry or change an old one.
@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Lister now goes busy while dealing with certain events, solving a few
  potential problems.
@{fg fill}o@{fg text} In an attempt to bypass the "lister falling off the port" bug some
  experimental code has been added to check for bogus 'inactive' events.
  If you ever get a requester from Opus saying it cannot find the Hotlist
  port, please report it to me or the DOpus5 Mailing List. If you used to
  experience this problem a lot and no longer do, please let me know as
  well.

@{fg shine}v1.2 -- 18/Oct/1996@{fg text}
o Now @{" requires " LINK requirements} AmigaOS 2.1. If you're still using 2.0 there's no excuse
  as it's a software-only upgrade and you should have 3.x now anyway.
@{fg fill}o@{fg text} German language catalog now included & installed by Installer script.
  Huge thanks to @{fg shine}Georg Rottlaender@{fg text} for the translations and his extremely
  fast response time in converting the extra strings for this version.
@{fg fill}o@{fg text} If you change the icon image/snapshot/tooltypes for this AmigaGuide you
  no longer have to worry about the Installer script overwritting it.
@{fg fill}o@{fg text} You can now @{" duplicate " LINK u_adding_entries} existing hotlist entries.
@{fg fill}o@{fg text} You can now @{" drag'n'drop " LINK u_adding_entries} entries from one hotlist to another to copy them.
@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Hotlist config files are now protected by a semaphore, and notification
  is used to keep all open hotlists up-to-date. This means that, so long
  as your filesystem supports notification (most do these days), it should
  be perfectly safe to use @{" multiple hotlists " LINK multihotlists}, even if you alter the
  config data in two at the same time.
@{fg fill}o@{fg text} If you now add a hotlist.module config file to a hotlist,
  @{" doubleclicking " LINK u_using_entries} on it will replace the current hotlist. In effect you
  can have sub-hotlists in a directory-like tree structure. Shift-clicking
  them opens a new hotlist, and the @{" parent gadget " LINK u_parent_gadget} will take you back
  through previously used hotlists. The @{" parent gadget " LINK u_parent_gadget} also supports
  shift-clicking and still works as it did when you are using the
  entry-level hotlist.
@{fg fill}o@{fg text} You can easily create sub-hotlists by @{" adding a new entry " LINK u_adding_entries} with your
  @{fg fill}MakeDir@{fg text} button and giving the path of a file which does not yet exist.
  This will create an entry for the hotlist which you can @{" doubleclick " LINK u_using_entries} on,
  and you can then @{" drop " LINK u_adding_entries} files into the new hotlist.
@{fg fill}o@{fg text} You can @{" drop " LINK u_using_entries} sub-hotlists on other Opus listers to read the hotlist
  into them.
@{fg fill}o@{fg text} The new @{" LISTER " LINK arguments} argument allows you to explicitly state which lister the
  hotlist should open in.
@{fg fill}o@{fg text} A new @{" filetype " LINK filetype} is included which matches hotlist.module config files
  and lets you doubleclick on them in normal listers to read their hotlists
  in. It will also give you an @{fg fill}Open Hotlist@{fg text} item in the pop-up menu for
  hotlist.module config files.

@endnode
@NODE future "hotlist.module: the future"

@{fg shine}The Future of Hotlist:
@{fg shine}----------------------@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}--@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--- -- -  -@{fg text}
In v1.1 I said:

    @{i}If I get REALLY bored sometime in the future I'll add the use of
    notification to automatically re-read the config file (and protect
    it from writting by a semaphore or something), and maybe even make
    it possible to drag'n'drop entries from one hotlist to another (of
    different config file) to copy them. But probably not -- I've got
    more useful things to write than these bells-and-whistles. @{ui}

I guess I got really bored because I did all those things for v1.2 ...
Right now I don't have any further ideas for this particular module.

@{fg shine}More modules?@{fg text}
@{fg shine}----------------------@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}--@{fg fill}-@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--@{fg shine}-@{fg fill}--- -- -  -@{fg text}
As well as many other add-ons for Opus including numerous ARexx scripts,
the wonderfully simply yet extremely useful (IMO) CDOpus (in Assembler),
the very-nice-indeedy (IMO) compare.module (in C), I have also contributed
to the creation of the MagicWorkbench-DOpus icon set (Trevor Morris
deserves as much if not more credit, although I did initiate the project),
and an AmigaGuide to the ARexx commands of Directory Opus. I also wrote
about half a page of the manual to Opus 5.5 and have myself hidden
somewhere in Opus itself. :-) Yes, I'm Opus obsessed and possessed.
I still manage to have something of a life. Well, you have to eat, don't
you? It sure does beat writting /X BBS utilities, at any rate.

Among other things I want to write the final-be-all-and-end-all xpk.module
for Opus, basically taking my most recent attempt (DOpusPack or whatever
I called it) and making it perfect, which I can finally do now that the
OpusSDK is here. I'll probably include xfddecrunch.library support too,
for the hell of it. Finding the time is going to be a problem though. :-(

After that I may disolve a few small ARexx scripts (and DOpusFuncs) into
a 'C' module, and then maybe write a beavis.module who follows the
mouse pointer with his eyes, speaks randomly, and moves his mouth when
he speaks.

@endnode
